"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The numpy.sinc function computes the normalized sinc function, which is defined as sin(pi*x)/(pi*x) for x != 0 and 1 for x == 0. Therefore, the expected results for the given input array [0, 1, 2, 3] are [1, sin(pi)/pi, sin(2*pi)/(2*pi), sin(3*pi)/(3*pi)]. The assertions in the code are incorrect because sinc(1) is not equal to 0.\",\n  \"patch\": \"7,8c7,8\\n< assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n< assert sinc_result[1] == 0, \\\"Results not equal to zero\\\"\\n---\\n> assert sinc_result[0] == 1, \\\"Results not equal to one\\\"\\n> assert np.isclose(sinc_result[1], np.sin(np.pi)/np.pi), \\\"Results not equal to sin(pi)/pi\\\"\\n\"\n}"